able, gradient-based learning across diverse languages. This represents a paradigm shift: from *correcting* miscalibration to *preventing* it via structured inductive biases in attention. The method enhances both reliability and interpretability, as attention patterns become sensitive to calibration needs. Furthermore, it generalizes better to unseen languages because it learns typological priors during training, aligning with findings in Paper 2 about meta-learning and parameter sharing. By combining insights from calibration theory, meta-learning, and attention control, this approach offers a more fundamental solution to trustworthy multilingual AI.

