2025-12-10 22:44:47.181 | WARNING  | agentscope.message.msg:__init__:145 - A new field `role` is newly added to the message. Please specify the role of the message. Currently we use a default "assistant" value.Scientist1: Thought: The core challenge in deploying Massively Multilingual Language Models (MMLMs) for low-resource languages lies not only in performance but also in reliability—specifically, the trustworthiness of their predicted confidences. While prior work (e.g., Paper 1) has shown that few-shot learning and post-hoc calibration can improve calibration, and meta-learning (Paper 2) enables smarter knowledge transfer across languages, there remains a critical gap: these approaches treat calibration and learning as sequential or independent processes. Moreover, existing methods often apply uniform calibration strategies across all languages, ignoring the heterogeneity in linguistic typology and data scarcity. My intuition is that calibration should be *adaptive*, *interactive*, and *meta-aware*—not just a final adjustment step, but an integral part of the few-shot learning loop. By designing a bidirectional framework where calibration informs learning and learning refines calibration—what I call "Calibrate-to-Learn, Learn-to-Calibrate"—we can create a self-improving system particularly effective for typologically distant, low-resource languages. This idea integrates meta-calibration (a novel concept inspired by meta-learning) with dynamic few-shot adaptation, going beyond static temperature scaling or label smoothing. It differs from prior work by making calibration a *learnable, language-specific, and context-sensitive* process guided by meta-knowledge about linguistic uncertainty patterns. Unlike Paper 1’s focus on zero/few-shot calibration as a downstream fix, or Paper 2’s use of meta-learning for instance selection, this proposal embeds calibration into the meta-learning objective itself, enabling models to learn *how to calibrate* during adaptation.

