2025-12-10 22:45:31.760 | WARNING  | agentscope.message.msg:__init__:145 - A new field `role` is newly added to the message. Please specify the role of the message. Currently we use a default "assistant" value.Scientist1: Thought: While the original "Calibrate-to-Learn, Learn-to-Calibrate" (CLLC) framework presents a compelling bidirectional integration of few-shot learning and calibration via a meta-calibrator, it treats calibration as an auxiliary correction applied *after* or *alongside* adaptation. Drawing inspiration from Papers 1–3—particularly their insights on how training dynamics affect calibration and the need for graded correctness in complex outputs—I propose a more radical shift: embedding calibration directly into the few-shot learning *objective* itself, not just as a post-hoc refinement but as a co-optimized, differentiable component of model updating. The key insight is that miscalibration in low-resource languages stems not only from poor confidence scaling but from misaligned gradient signals during rapid adaptation. Standard few-shot fine-tuning can overfit to spurious patterns in small support sets, especially in typologically distant languages, leading to high-confidence errors. Instead of correcting this *afterward*, we should shape the adaptation process to favor updates that are both accurate *and* reliably confident. My new idea introduces **Gradient-Aware Calibration Regularization (GACR)**, a method that injects a calibration-aware loss into the inner loop of few-shot learning, penalizing parameter updates that increase predictive confidence without proportional gains in correctness. This is achieved by dynamically estimating calibration error (e.g., ECE) over the support set during adaptation and backpropagating through this metric to regularize gradients. Crucially, GACR uses a **language-adaptive uncertainty prior**, derived from linguistic metadata and precomputed calibration baselines across languages, to modulate the strength of regularization—applying stronger constraints where models are historically prone to overconfidence (e.g., low-resource, non-Latin script languages). Unlike static calibration or post-hoc meta-calibrators, GACR makes reliability an intrinsic part of learning, enabling the model to “learn calibratability” during adaptation. Furthermore, I extend evaluation beyond classification to include long-form generation tasks (e.g., multilingual summarization), incorporating partial correctness via distributional calibration metrics inspired by Paper 3. This transforms calibration from a downstream fix into a foundational mechanism for trustworthy multilingual generalization.

New Idea: ```json{
  "Idea": "We propose a paradigm shift in the adaptation of Massively Multilingual Language Models (MMLMs): integrating calibration as a core, differentiable component of few-shot learning through Gradient-Aware Calibration Regularization (GACR). Rather than treating calibration as a separate post-processing step or auxiliary network, GACR embeds a dynamic calibration loss directly into the inner-loop optimization of few-shot adaptation, ensuring that parameter updates do not merely maximize accuracy but also preserve or improve confidence reliability. Specifically, during each few-shot episode, we compute a differentiable approximation of Expected Calibration Error (ECE) over the model’s support set predictions and combine it with the standard cross-entropy loss using a language-specific adaptive weight. This weight is determined by a lightweight calibration sensitivity function that considers typological distance from English, token frequency, script type, and historical miscalibration trends observed in zero-shot settings. By backpropagating through the ECE term, GACR discourages sharp confidence increases unless matched by actual performance gains—effectively preventing overconfident overfitting on small, noisy few-shot sets. To handle languages with minimal supervision, we further introduce a meta-learning stage where the calibration sensitivity function is optimized across diverse language episodes to generalize to unseen low-resource cases. We extend our framework to long-form generation tasks (e.g., multilingual summarization, open-ended QA) by adopting a distributional calibration approach: instead of binary correctness, we use semantic similarity scores (e.g., BERTScore) between predicted and reference outputs to define graded correctness, then align model confidence (e.g., average token entropy or self-rated certainty) with this continuous correctness distribution. This enables calibration assessment even when responses are partially correct—a critical advancement for real-world multilingual applications. Our framework is compatible with any gradient-based few-shot method (e.g., MAML, Prototypical Networks adapted to MMLMs) and plug-and-play with models like XLM-R and mT5. We evaluate GACR across 35 languages spanning high-, medium-, and low-resource groups, using classification (XNLI, PAWS-X) and generation tasks (mXSum, MLQA-long). Metrics include task performance (F1, ROUGE), calibration error (ECE, MCE), and robustness under domain shift. We expect GACR to reduce ECE by >20% in low-resource languages while maintaining or improving accuracy, outperforming both static calibration and the original CLLC framework by creating a tighter coupling between learning and reliability.",
